# [PCE](../wg/pce.html)

## Summary

The Path Computation Element (PCE) Working Group met at IETF 126. The session covered working group status updates, active drafts, and several new proposals. Key topics included operational clarifications, performance metrics, Segment Routing (SR) point-to-multipoint (P2MP) policies, binding label extensions, Network Resource Partition (NRP) extensions, path delay differences, computing-aware traffic steering (CATS), precision availability metrics, and implicit TLS profiles.

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Working Group Status
* **Presenter**: Julien Meuric
* **Slides**: [1. Introduction](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-1-introduction-01)
* **Discussion**:
  * The working group has published 77 RFCs, with 6 drafts currently with the IESG and 16 active working group documents.
  * The chairs discussed progressing `draft-ietf-pce-entropy-label-position` soon.
  * Progression of `draft-ietf-pce-sr-path-segment` is waiting on the corresponding SPRING document to resolve normative references.
  * Progression of `draft-ietf-pce-pcep-extension-pce-controller-p2mp` is also a near-term target.
  * Susan Hares discussed coordination between BGP/IDR/BEST and PCE regarding P2MP drafts and tunnels, suggesting a removable appendix to capture cross-working-group details.
  * Ketan Talaulikar noted that protocol extensions in PCE and IDR should closely align with the base specifications developed in the technology working groups (e.g., SPRING).

### 2. Operational Clarification
* **Presenter**: Andrew Stone
* **Slides**: [2.1 Operational Clarification](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-21-operational-clarification-00)
* **Draft**: `draft-ietf-pce-operational`
* **Discussion**:
  * Andrew Stone presented updates addressing feedback from Adrian Farrel, improving terminology and description clarity.
  * New text was added to clarify behavior under PCE overload: PCCs should continue to send reports to keep the PCE updated on state changes, but should apply local policy throttling where possible.
  * Julien Meuric suggested that the overload behavior text should also consider other message types, such as performance measurement notifications or auto-bandwidth updates.
  * Dhruv Dhody emphasized keeping this document strictly focused on clarifying existing behaviors rather than introducing new protocol amendments. Ketan Talaulikar agreed to review the draft and provide feedback on how the IESG might interpret this type of informational clarification document.

### 3. Stateful Amendment
* **Presenter**: Andrew Stone
* **Slides**: [2.2 Stateful Amendment](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-22-stateful-amendment-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * This draft propose updates to stateful PCEP RFCs regarding stateful LSP bring-up (skipping PC requests), discouraging SR-RO/SRv6-RO (since ERO reflects the actual path), and handling orphan PCE LSPs (discouraging delegation reclaim and relying on PCC re-delegation).
  * Julien Meuric suggested adding text to clarify that during stateful bring-up updates, the PCE may remain quiet and the PCC should not always expect an update unless a path change is needed. Andrew Stone agreed to add this clarification.
  * The authors requested working group adoption.

### 4. Performance Metrics
* **Presenter**: Rakesh Gandhi
* **Slides**: [2.3 Performance Metrics](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-pcep-extensions-for-performance-measurement-for-sr-te-and-mpls-te-lsps-with-stateful-pce-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * This draft defines PCEP extensions to measure delay, loss, liveness, and bandwidth utilization.
  * The update introduces PCEP notification messages to report measurements, optimized to omit ERO and RRO overhead.
  * Lei Zheng questioned the meaning of the "look back" (L) flag for delay. Rakesh Gandhi explained it represents a loopback measurement (T4 - T1) when intermediate timestamps (T2, T3) are unavailable, and agreed to add references to the SRPM specification.
  * Fan Yang suggested referencing existing IGP unidirectional link delay metrics. Rakesh Gandhi agreed to add context mapping these metrics.
  * A poll was taken in the room; there was strong interest in adoption, with one objection. The chairs requested the objector post their concerns to the mailing list.

### 5. SR P2MP Policy
* **Presenter**: Hooman Bidgoli
* **Slides**: [3.1 SR P2MP Policy](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-31-sr-p2mp-policy-00)
* **Draft**: `draft-ietf-pce-sr-p2mp-policy`
* **Discussion**:
  * Hooman Bidgoli presented the differences between v14 and v19, clarifying that the current scope is MPLS-only (SRv6 will be addressed in a separate draft). The updates include enhanced error codes, inclusion of Fast Reroute (FRR) multipath backup TLVs, CCI objects in PCUpdate messages, and BNF cleanups.
  * Susan Hares commented on the relationship between BGP/EVPN and PCEP for P2MP, emphasizing the need to document how conflicts are handled if multiple controllers attempt to provision the same replication segments.
  * Dhruv Dhody requested the working group review the message flow diagrams in the appendix during the ongoing Working Group Last Call (WGLC), as it introduces a new pictorial representation style.
  * Zafar Ali requested clarifications regarding the FRR section (4.3.6), which will be addressed on the mailing list.

### 6. Binding Label/SID Extensions
* **Presenter**: Samuel Sidor
* **Slides**: [3.2 Binding Label/SID Extensions](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-32-binding-labelsid-extensions-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * Samuel Sidor presented proposed extensions to handle fallback behaviors when binding SID allocation fails due to conflicts. Fallbacks include keeping the LSP down during conflicts or allocating a local binding label and reporting it back to the PCE.
  * Recent updates include renaming capability flags, defining TLV ordering, and enhancing error handling. The authors requested working group adoption.

### 7. Extensions for Network Resource Partition (NRP)
* **Presenter**: Lei Zheng
* **Slides**: [4.1 Extensions for Network Resource Partition (NRP)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-41-extensions-for-network-resource-partition-nrp-00)
* **Draft**: `draft-ietf-pce-pcep-nrp`
* **Discussion**:
  * The draft has been updated to rename the "RP TLV" to "RP ID TLV" to align with BGP terminology. It defines NRP-aware path computation and path initiation.
  * Zafar Ali pointed out a dependency on the SPRING draft `draft-ietf-spring-sr-policy-nrp` (which defines the data model). Jie Dong and Dhruv Dhody agreed that while the PCEP draft is broader, an informative reference to the SPRING draft should be added.
  * Dhruv Dhody advised the authors to make the description of NRP path computation constraints more specific (e.g., node/link filtering and resource allocation) rather than using a generic "should" clause, and to address recent IESG comments on NRP terminology.

### 8. Path Delay Difference
* **Presenter**: Yao Liu
* **Slides**: [4.2 Path Delay Difference](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-42-path-delay-difference-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * This draft proposes a multipath delay difference metric to ensure the latency difference between multiple paths within an LSP does not exceed a threshold.
  * Andrew Stone questioned the P2MP use case, noting that optimizing for lowest delay across all branches is more practical; if a difference constraint cannot be met, returning no path at all is worse than having delay differences.
  * Hooman Bidgoli advised coordinating with the PIM working group, explaining that multicast trees must be optimized as a whole rather than per-branch, and re-optimizing live multicast trees during transmission is operationally disruptive.
  * Dhruv Dhody recommended focusing on the most viable use case and simplifying the draft.

### 9. Extensions for Computing-Aware Traffic Steering (CATS)
* **Presenter**: Fan Yang
* **Slides**: [4.3 Extensions for Computing-Aware Traffic Steering](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-slides-for-draft-xf-pce-cats-service-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * This proposal introduces PCEP extensions to support CATS. It defines a new metric type for computing metrics, a C-flag in the LSP Attribute (LSPA) object to trigger CATS path computation, and TLVs to carry Service IDs (CSID) and Service Instance IDs (CSCIID).
  * The next step is to align terminology and definitions with the CATS working group documents.

### 10. Precision Availability Metrics
* **Presenter**: Luis M. Contreras
* **Slides**: [4.4 Precision Availability Metrics](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-44-precision-availability-metrics-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * Luis M. Contreras presented a change in direction based on previous feedback. Instead of defining a dedicated precision metric object, the draft now reuses the existing Objective Function (OF) framework (RFC 5541).
  * It defines three new objective functions: highest compliance with precision availability metrics, minimum violated intervals, and minimum severe violated intervals.

### 11. Implicit TLS in PCEP
* **Presenter**: Zafar Ali
* **Slides**: [4.5 Implicit TLS in PCEP](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-pce-draft-ali-pce-implicit-tls-profile-00)
* **Discussion**:
  * Zafar Ali presented an informational proposal for policy-driven implicit TLS profiles. Under this profile, if both peers are pre-configured to use TLS, they initiate the TLS handshake directly over TCP without executing the StartTLS negotiation (RFC 8253) in cleartext.
  * Dhruv Dhody noted that during the design of RFC 8253, security area reviews favored StartTLS. He advised engaging security experts early to address how this profile affects backward compatibility and potential security concerns.
  * Hooman Bidgoli noted that other protocols like RADIUS support bringing up TLS immediately after the TCP connection is established, which aligns with the implicit TLS approach.

